John Edwards: Language skills are vital for global citizens
Scotland’s independent schools have a reputation for excellence and have maintained this reputation in 2018, when once again outstanding exam results were obtained, further enhanced by individual and collective achievements in sports, the arts in music and other social events.
These schools, with a total of 30,000 students in Scotland and represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the best level for their students and their parents.
Independent schools have set the goal of preparing their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers, and their lives as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement specific school programs, we see that modern languages are still a popular and desirable subject in our schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, it persists in his consciousness.
If you speak his native language, it remains in his heart."
It is a reassuring reminder that we cannot simply rely on English when we want to build relationships and win the trust of people from other countries.
Taking into account the recent results of this year's exams, we can see that the languages are at the top of the league tables with the largest number of exams passed in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who taught foreign languages reached the highest mark of A.
Data from the Board of Independent Schools of Scotland for 74 schools show that 72 percent of students got the highest mark in A Chinese, and 72 percent who learned German also got the same mark, 69 percent who learned French and 63 percent who learned Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages, as a subject of choice, are now valued as highly in independent school programs as in science-technology-engineering and mathematics group subjects.
A 2014 survey by the British Commission for Employment and Skills found that 17 percent of employers cited lack of language skills as a reason to be unable to fill vacancies.
As a result, language skills are becoming increasingly mandatory in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
These skills are essential in a globalised world, with increasing job opportunities requiring language skills.
Regardless of their chosen career, learning a foreign language will give them the real advantage of such a long-term skill in the future.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically improve the competitiveness of a multi-language speaker.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent did not speak a foreign language well enough to sustain the conversation, while French was the only one spoken by a double-digit number of people, 15 percent.
That is why contributing to language learning is important for today's children.
Multi-language skills, especially in developing countries, will give children a better chance for meaningful work.
Schools in Scotland differ in terms of the languages taught.
Some schools will focus more on the more common modern languages, while others will teach languages such as Chinese and Japanese, which are considered the most important for Britain's future, according to plans for 2020.
Whatever your child’s interests are, independent schools will always be able to choose from a range of languages and teachers will be experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a language environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
At the moment, in the global business environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still vital for the future of the country, so this fact must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be seen as "knowledges of international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer Scottish youth this choice, diversity and excellence.
Il faut bien le faire (It must be done).
John Edwards is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
