North Korea said it would not unilaterally disarm, without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the continuation of sanctions deepened its distrust of the United States, and North Korea would not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons in such a situation.
Ri Yong Ho informed the world organization's annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant good-will steps" last year, such as stopping nuclear and missile testing, dismantling the nuclear weapons test site, and promising never to spread nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we don't see an adequate U.S. response," he said.
"If there is no trust in the U.S., there will be no faith in our national security, and under such circumstances we will in no way unilaterally disarm the first."
Although Ri repeated the well-known North Korean accusations of Washington's resistance to a "gradual" approach to denuclearization, according to which Korea would be rewarded for steps taken gradually, his statement left an impression because it did not automatically reject unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang had done before.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first meeting of U.S. President and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim promised to work towards "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula" while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea's security.
North Korea has attempted to officially end the Korean War of 1950-53, but the United States has stated that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington also has not conceded the call to ease the serious international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The U.S. insists that "denuclearization should be first", and raises the level of pressure from sanctions to reach the goal by force, even opposing the "declaration of the end of the war," Ri said.
"The idea that sanctions could bring us to our knees is an empty fantasy cherished by people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions only deepens our distrust."
Ri did not talk about intentions for a second Kim meeting with Trump, whom the U.S. leader had specifically mentioned while speaking at the United Nations this week.
In his speech, the minister specifically singled out three meetings of Kim with South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added, "If the other side on this denuclearization issue were South Korea, not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to such a dead end."
However, Ri's tone of speech differed dramatically from that of last year when he stated in the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korea's missiles on the U.S. mainland was inevitable after "Evil Mr. President" Trump had called Kim a "missile" on a suicide mission.
This year, at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, lauded Kim for his courage in taking steps towards disarmament, but stressed that there was still a lot to do, and that sanctions should be maintained until North Korea's nuclear program was denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump stated that he had not scheduled a specific time, stressing that "it doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia stress that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for what it has done.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that, "The implementation of Security Council sanctions must be vigorously pursued without making mistakes until definitive and conclusive denuclearization is achieved."
The Security Council has unanimously stepped up sanctions since 2006 in an attempt to make Pyongyang's nuclear- and ballistic-weapon-related programmes unfettered.
