Harvard University students will learn how to relax enough
A new subject at Harvard University this year has made students sleep more, and it is an attempt to counter the increasingly popular culture of brutalism, which involves a caffeine-filled study through the night.
One teacher found that students at the world's best university often don't even have a basic knowledge of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed a subject that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
The inspiration to create a new subject occurred to him after speaking about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end, a girl came up to me and asked, 'Why are I only being told this now that I'm in my last year?'
She found that no one had ever explained to her how important sleep was to me -- which surprised me, he told Telegraph.
This year, for the first time, the first edition of the course provides students with basic information on how good sleep habits contribute to achievement in learning and sports, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services informed that the university decided to introduce the course after learning that the students were suffering from a serious lack of sleep during the school week.
The lesson-long training process includes series of interactive tasks.
One of the parts is a dormitory door image where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how performance in sports is affected by sleep deprivation and the importance of the bedtime routine.
In another part, students are informed about how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Then a campus map with interactive icons invites participants to rethink their daily routine.
"We know that this will not immediately change student behavior.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know how smoking will affect your health," added Professor Chaisler.
He said that the culture of being proud of being able to learn all night long still exists, and added that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students meant that lack of sleep became an increasingly serious problem.
He explained that providing enough quality sleep should be the students' "secret weapon" to combat stress, burnout, and anxiety, and even to prevent weight gain, because the lack of sleep switches the brains into fasting mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chaser develop the subject, after taking one of the professor's lectures last year, in Harvard's first course.
He said that the subject had opened his eyes and inspired him to make the course accessible to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask students who receive a postgraduate education to learn a similar program before going to enjoy the competition.
Professor Chaser advises students to install an alarm not only for the time they will rise, but also when they will go to bed, as well as keep in mind how people are harmed by the "blue lights" emitted by electronic device screens and LED lamps, as they can disrupt circadian rhythms, making it difficult to fall asleep.
