The Global Citizen Festival, launched in 2012, is an event created by the international advocacy group the Global Poverty Project, which hopes to end poverty by attracting more and more people who are actively fighting poverty.
In order to receive a free ticket to this event (unless there was a desire to pay for a VIP ticket), concert visitors had to complete a series of tasks or "acts", such as doing voluntary work, sending an email to a world leader, making a phone call, or some other significant activity to raise awareness of ending poverty.
But how successful has the Global Citizen movement been, with 12 more years left to achieve its goal?
Is the idea of giving a free concert a good way to persuade people to take action, or is it just another case of so-called "clitivism" where people feel they are truly able to influence something by signing an online petition or sending a Twitter message?
The Global Citizen movement claims to have recorded over 19 million "activities" from its supporters since 2011 in an effort to achieve various goals.
It reports that these actions have helped world leaders announce commitments and policies equivalent to more than US$37 billion, which will affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
