The new study, which is being conducted at a Scottish Highland estate, is aimed at discovering how bats use the landscape in the process of searching for food.
The findings are expected to bring new clarity to the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and to assist in their protection measures in the future.
Scientists from Scotland's National Trust will study dwarf bats, pygmy bats, as well as brown long-eared and water-dwelling night bats in Invereve Gardens in Westeros.
Special recorders will be placed in the main locations on the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
Sound experts will analyze all records to determine the frequency of bat calls and which species perform the specific actions.
A habitat map and report will then be developed to create a detailed view of the landscape reflecting the behaviour of the bats.
NTS conservation advisor Rob Dewar hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat management works such as the creation of meadows and how best to preserve forests for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has shrunk significantly over the past century.
These lands are threatened by construction and development work affecting bat hideouts and loss of residence.
Wind generators and lighting can also pose risks, as can flypaper and chemical treatments for some building materials, as well as attacks by cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes during hunting.
They use a sophisticated echo-location method to find insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes the problem of bats very seriously.
The organization has ten trained experts who regularly carry out surveys, bat hide checks and sometimes even rescue operations.
The organization has even established in Scotland the first and only "Threave" property of specially designed bats in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of the ten bat species found in Scotland.
Property manager David Thompson claims that this area is ideal for bats.
"Here's a great place for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, a lot of ancient trees and a generally suitable habitat.
But there's plenty more we don't know about bats, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to survive."
He stressed the importance of checking for bats in the area before carrying out property maintenance work, as one female hiding place may result in the killing of up to 400 females and their young, potentially destroying the entire local population.
Bats are protected animals and should not be killed, tormented, disturbed or destroyed by their hiding places.
Elizabeth Ferrell, an employee of the Bat Conservation Trust in Scotland, has called on the public to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about bats, and for a number of their species we just don't know how they're doing."
